Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[In ProMED-mail 20080830.2712, the Freep article specifically said
that EHD (epizootic hemorrhagic disease) had been ruled out. Now the
DNR is coming back and saying it has been diagnosed. This had to have
been a miscommunication somewhere along the line, as laboratories may
say the testing is not complete, but they rarely reverse themselves,
as these conflicting articles have.

Epizootic hemorrhagic disease (EHD) is closely related to bluetongue
virus infection (BTV). Both diseases are carried by biting midges.
Recently Europe has experienced a significant upswing in BTV. It also
moved further north than had previously been thought possible. EHD
may be following a similar pattern. This could indicate the virus is
changing its virulence or has become more resistant to cold weather.
The virus has, in some way, changed its character. As such, it means
veterinarians and producers in more regions not previously seeing EHD
will now need to add this disease to their differential list. - Mod.TG

Oakland and Macomb counties are located in eastern Michigan and can
be seen on the map at
<http://www.mapsofworld.com/usa/states/michigan/michigan-maps/michigan-county-map.jpg>.
- CopyEd.MJ]
